@node Quick start, What is needed to build R, Building R from sources, Building R from sources
@section Quick start

If you have a clean, recent Mac OS X (10.5 Leopard or later) and want
quick instructions how to build your own R binary, read this section. In
all other cases please read the details in the following sections.

First, you need to install the developer tools -- that is
@command{Xcode}.  For recent versions of OS X this is available from the
App Store: for earlier versions it is on the OS X installation DVD
(where applicable) but the latest version can be downloaded from
@uref{http://developer.apple.com/}.

Xcode 4.3 and higher (available for Mac OS X 10.7 and higher) no longer
installs command line tools in the system location, they need to be
downloaded and installed separately.   At least with 4.5 and higher you
can do so by launching Xcode, opening Preferences, selecting Downloads
and installing `Command Line Tools'.

Xcode needs to be at least version 3.1 for Mac OS X 10.5 (Leopard) and
Xcode 3.2 for Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard).

Then download and install the @command{gcc-4.2} and @command{gfortran}
compilers from @uref{http://r.research.att.com/tools/}.

Optionally you can install TeX (@uref{http://www.tug.org/mactex/}) to
build documentation.  You can pick useful external libraries from
@uref{http://r.research.att.com/libs/} (such as readline, libpng, jpeg,
tiff) but they are not essential.  You can install them using the Terminal
(in Application/Utilities) for example:

@example
curl -s -S http://r.research.att.com/libs/readline-5.2-12-darwin8-bin4.tar.gz \
| sudo tar fvxz - -C /
@end example

Note that they all unpack into @file{/usr/local}, hence the use of
@command{sudo}.

Download, configure and build @R{}. In the following we assume you have
an Intel-based Mac with 64-bit support. Again in Terminal type:

@example
# download R
curl -O http://cran.r-project.org/src/base/R-2/R-2.15.2.tar.gz
# unpack R
tar fxz R-2.15.2.tar.gz
# choose the architecture (x86_64 or i386)
arch=x86_64
# create a build directory
mkdir R-$arch
cd R-$arch
# configure R
../R-2.15.2/configure r_arch=$arch  CC="gcc-4.2 -arch $arch" \
     CXX="g++-4.2 -arch $arch" F77="gfortran-4.2 -arch $arch" \
     FC="gfortran-4.2 -arch $arch" OBJC="gcc-4.2 -arch $arch" \
     --x-includes=/usr/X11/include --x-libraries=/usr/X11/lib
# build R: use more processes if you have many cores.  
make -j4
# At this point you can run R as `bin/R' even without installing

# install R
make install
# in some cases you may need to use ``sudo make install'' instead
@end example

If you want a 32-bit Intel build replace @code{arch=x86_64} with
@code{arch=i386}. (For PowerPC use @code{arch=ppc} (32-bit) or
@code{arch=ppc64}.  These are currently untested and were only supported
on Mac OS X 10.5.)  You can repeat the steps above for any number of
architectures.

In order to make the newly installed R visible from the command line, use

@example
sudo ln -sfn /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/bin/R /usr/bin/R
@end example

Please note that any version of R you build yourself will be different
from the released binary @CRAN{} version and may not work with the
package binaries we provide. Therefore we recommend using the @CRAN{}
binary or nightly builds from @uref{http://R.research.att.com} unless
you want to modify R sources yourself.  However, builds following these
instructions default to using source installations of packages, so
incompatibility with binary packages is only a problem if you share an
@R{} library of packages between versions of R.

