@node Development tools, Fortran compiler, What is needed to build R, What is needed to build R
@subsection Development tools

If you have Mac OS X 10.7 (Lion) or higher and Xcode 4.3 or higher, you
will need to install ``Command Line Tools for Xcode``. Those are
available from the Apple Mac Developer website or for recent Xcode, from
within Xcode (see the previous section). Xcode alone is no longer
sufficient.

These versions of Xcode (and some versions of 4.2) do not include the
compilers used to build @CRAN{} distributions of @R{}: these can be
downloaded from @uref{http://R.research.att.com/tools/}.  For example,
for Lion or Mountain Lion, install
@uref{http://r.research.att.com/tools/gcc-42-5666.3-darwin11.pkg} (at
the time of writing: this includes a Fortran compiler).

Earlier versions of Xcode contain usable C/C++ compilers, provided the
version is at least 4.2.

It is also possible to use @command{clang} or the LLVM-based
@command{gcc} in recent versions of Xcode, but you will still need
@command{gfortran}.

@node Fortran compiler, readline 4.3 or higher (optional), Development tools, What is needed to build R
@subsection Fortran compiler

Unfortunately the Xcode Tools do not include a Fortran compiler. You need
to install a version of the Fortran compiler from GCC which is built for
Mac OS X. We provide GNU Fortran builds that can be added to Apple's
Xcode tools -- see @uref{http://r.research.att.com/tools/}. The @CRAN{}
binaries are configured to use Apple's gcc and the supplied Fortran
compiler (see also @pxref{Why do I need custom compilers for the CRAN
binary?}).

@node readline 4.3 or higher (optional), X11 window server (optional), Fortran compiler, What is needed to build R
@subsection readline 4.3 or higher (optional)
The readline library is optional as. Mac OS X 10.4 (Tiger) and later
come with the @samp{libedit} library which emulates
readline. Nevertheless, GNU readline has some additional functionality
so it is worth installing.

Readline is necessary if you want to be able to retrieve history using
use arrow keys or for @key{TAB} completion of filenames when you run R
as a command line tool. The sources can be found @emph{via}
@uref{http://cnswww.cns.cwru.edu/php/chet/readline/rltop.html}

How to install a binary build of readline is described under @ref{Quick start}.

Readline 5.0 and later compile out-of-the box, however it is recommended
to use @code{make CPPFLAGS=-DNEED_EXTERN_PC}, because the configure
script fails to detect that flag. The use of readline 5.2 with recent
patches is recommended due to bugs in earlier versions that can lead to
crashes. (We cannot distribute readline 6.0 on @CRAN{} due to its
incompatible licensing terms.)

To compile readline, uncompress the source archive and follow the standard installation sequence:
@example
./configure
make CPPFLAGS=-DNEED_EXTERN_PC
sudo make install
@end example
It installs everything in @file{/usr/local}.

@emph{Note:} It is possible to build multi-architecture readline binary
in one step, for example set @samp{CC='gcc -arch i386 -arch x86_64'} to
build both currrent architectures (see the Apple Xcode tools reference
for details).

@node X11 window server (optional), Cairo graphics library (optional), readline 4.3 or higher (optional), What is needed to build R
@subsection X11 window server (optional)
X11 window system is necessary to use the X11 device in R and other
devices that rely on X11.

Mac OS X 10.8 (Mountain Lion) does not include X11.  You can install it
from the XQuartz project: @uref{http://xquartz.macosforge.org/landing/}.
XQuartz's builds can also be used with earlier versions of OS X and some
users have found them more stable.

Mac OS X 10.7 (Lion) includes a usable installation of X11.

Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard) requires manual identification of X11
location when configuring @R{} using @code{--x-includes=/usr/X11/include
--x-libraries=/usr/X11/lib}.

Mac OS X 10.5 (Leopard) installs X11 by default. Also
@code{/usr/X11/bin} must be on the @code{PATH} in order for @R{} to
recognize X11 properly (e.g.@: by issuing @code{export
PATH=/usr/X11/bin:$PATH}).

@c Mac OS X 10.3 (Panther) and 10.4 (Tiger) include X11 on the installation
@c CD/DVD, however, it is not selected by default. If it is not installed,
@c you can re-install it using the original installation CD/DVD.

@c To install X11 on those systems, follow these steps:

@c @enumerate
@c @item
@c Insert Mac OS X Disk 1 (CD/DVD) that came with your Mac

@c @item
@c @key{Ctrl}-Click (or right button click) on "Install Bundled Software Only", select "Show Original"

@c @item
@c double-click on "X11User.pkg"
@c @end enumerate

@c If you have a retail version of OS X, replace second step by
@c @enumerate 2
@c @item
@c Go to @samp{System/Installation/Packages} direrctory on the DVD
@c @end enumerate

@c In addition to the user part, you need to install the X11 SDK package from the Xcode Tools CD. In Xcode 2.4.0 and higher this is the default if X11 is installed, therefore it is important to install X11 before installing Xcode.

@c Mac OS X 10.2 (Jaguar) does not include an X11 installer. However, there
@c are two options to obtain X11: Apple released X11 beta for Jaguar which
@c is still around, although not officially supported. It features the
@c Quartz window manager that integrates nicely into the system. If you are
@c unable to find Apple's X11 beta, you will need to install both the X11
@c Window server and the X11 SDK package from the XFree86 web page. Other
@c versions such as using fink are available, too.

@node Cairo graphics library (optional), X11 Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), X11 window server (optional), What is needed to build R
@subsection Cairo graphics library (optional)

@R{} 2.7.0 and later include support for cairo graphics library as one
of the options in X11 support. Mac OS X does not include cairo library,
therefore we have to build our own. In order to simplify the
distribution, we use a static build of cairo. Therefore the library is
not needed at run time as it is already part of @R{}. However, if you
want to compile R, you can obtain the same binary we use for the release
from @uref{http://r.research.att.com/libs/}. Read more on @CRAN{} in the
``tools'' directory.

In general cairo graphics library can be obtained from
@uref{http://www.cairographics.org/}. More recent versions can use
either native ATSUI/Quartz font back-end or FreeType. If the latter is
used, make sure you get the most recent (even development) version
available, because there are known bugs in FreeType with respect to Mac
font support.

Cairo support is strictly optional given that @code{quartz()} is the
default graphics device on Mac OS X, but it can be useful for remote
displays.

@node X11 Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), Aqua Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), Cairo graphics library (optional), What is needed to build R
@subsection X11 Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional)


If you plan to use the @code{tcltk} package for @R{}, you need to
install
@uref{http://cran.r-project.org/bin/macosx/tools/tcltk-8.5.5-x11.dmg}.
This was at one time part of the @R{} distribution but is now
distributed separately.

Alternatively you need to download the sources of the Tcl and Tk 8.5.x
(or 8.6.x) packages to build it yourself from the sources.  The original
sources can be found on the official Tcl/Tk web page
@uref{http://www.tcl.tk/software/tcltk/download.html}.  Please do the
following respecting the sequence (you'll be asked for an administrator
password). These are examples for version 8.5.5 of the Tcl and Tk
sources, you'll probably find new version on the web page, thus only the
name of the .tar.gz archives changes.

The following shell commands will download, compile and install universal Tcl/Tk. Modify the configure part to suit your needs, such as if you don't need all architectures:
@example
cd /tmp/
curl -O http://internap.dl.sourceforge.net/sourceforge/tcl/tcl8.5.5-src.tar.gz
curl -O http://internap.dl.sourceforge.net/sourceforge/tcl/tk8.5.5-src.tar.gz
tar fxz tcl8.5.5-src.tar.gz
cd tcl8.5.5/unix
CFLAGS='-arch i386 -arch x86_64' ./configure --with-x \
--disable-corefoundation --enable-threads --disable-symbols --disable-aqua
make
sudo make install

cd ../..
tar fxz tk8.5.5-src.tar.gz
cd tk8.5.5/unix
CFLAGS='-arch i386 -arch x86_64' ./configure --with-x \
--disable-corefoundation --enable-threads --disable-symbols --disable-aqua
make
sudo make install
@end example

(A 64-bit build of Tk will only work if you have 64-bit X11 installed --
this is the default on Leopard and later.)

@node Aqua Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), TeX suite of tools for documentation (optional), X11 Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), What is needed to build R
@subsection Aqua Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional)
Mac OS X 10.4 (Tiger) and later come with Aqua Tcl/Tk libraries. If
those are not detected automatically, use the following flags with
@code{configure}:
@example
--with-tcl-config=/System/Library/Frameworks/Tcl.framework/tclConfig.sh 
--with-tk-config=/System/Library/Frameworks/Tk.framework/tkConfig.sh
@end example

Note that currently @Rapp{} doesn't support Aqua Tcl/Tk, because of
conflicting event loops (in fact Aqua Tcl/Tk cannot be embedded in any
UI application due to its design assumptions). Therefore we strongly
discourage the use of Aqua Tcl/Tk with @Rapp{}.

However, for those using command-line @R{} only, building against Aqua
Tcl/Tk, e.g.@: as installed from
@uref{http://www.activestate.com/activetcl/downloads}, works well and is
a much more intuitive interface to Tk for experienced Mac users.

@node TeX suite of tools for documentation (optional),  , Aqua Tcl/Tk headers and libraries (optional), What is needed to build R
@subsection TeX suite of tools for documentation (optional)

Mac@TeX{} (@uref{http://www.tug.org/mactex/}) is the recommended TeX
installation as used on @CRAN{}, but it is over 1GB as a download and
3-4GB once installed.

The FAQ formerly recommended the @emph{i-Installer II} at
@uref{http://ii2.sourceforge.net/tex-index.html}, but it has been
unsupported since 2007.

@strong{Note:} You may also want to install @TeX{}Shop
(@uref{http://www.uoregon.edu/~koch/texshop/texshop.html}). Beside
wonderful GUI for editing @TeX{} files that page also provides many
useful links for @TeX{} on Mac OS X.

@node How to configure and build R, How to install R, What is needed to build R, Building R from sources
@section How to configure and build R
Download the latest sources of R from @CRAN{} or fetch them using SVN. Unpack the archive with tar -zxf @emph{name_of_R_sources_archive} and cd
inside the R sources directory. Then you need to configure R for your system and build R. It is recommended to use separate directory for building from the sources. For example if you unpacked @R{} at @file{R-2.15.2} type:
@example
mkdir build
cd build
../R-2.15.2/configure
make
@end example
This will configure R to be built as a Framework to be installed inside your @emph{/Library/Frameworks} directory with the name @emph{R.framework}. @code{make} will compile R. Such compiled @R{} can already be used by running the @code{bin/R} script.

Note that the default configuration assumes that all your compilers produce binaries for the same architecture. This is not true on Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow Leopard) where by default Xcode gcc produces 64-bit binaries but gfortran produces 32-bit binaries. Therefore in such a case you must set the compiler variables (@code{CC}, @code{CXX}, @code{OBJC}, @code{F77}, @code{FC}) accordingly to make sure they target the same architecture (see also @pxref{How to build universal R}).

Some additional, useful flags that you may want to add to configure include:
@itemize
@item
@code{--with-blas='-framework vecLib'} enables @code{vecLib} as BLAS implementation. Given that @code{vecLib} is highly optimized by Apple, it is recommended for most users. (Currently there is one exception: users with Nehalem-based Mac Pros may want to use other alternatives such as ATLAS because current vecLib fails to recognize cores on such machines and will run in single-threaded mode which is slow.)

@item
@code{--enable-BLAS-shlib} enables the use of @code{libRblas.dylib} which separates BLAS from the R library. This allows you to switch between various BLAS implementations (such as vecLib, internal R BLAS and ATLAS) without the need to re-compile R. It is in general a good idea and can be used with both internal BLAS and vecLib. (This option is enabled in the binary available from @CRAN{}.)

@c -- better keep quiet, it is not recommended --
@c @item
@c @code{--disable-R-framework} builds R the 'unix' way, not as a framework. This is in general not recommended, but users that want exactly the same layout as on other unix-alikes may prefer this. Note that this influences mainly the installation of R, not the compilation - in fact R compiled as a framework still behaves the 'unix' way until installed.
@end itemize

You can change the default location of the @emph{R.framework} 
installation at configure time by specifying the flag @code{--enable-R-framework[=DIR]}, i.e. 
with something like
@example
./configure --enable-R-framework=FOO
@end example
and the final destination of the @emph{R.framework} will be @emph{FOO/R.framework}, which means that you 
don't have to specify the @emph{R.framework} text in the path. 

The R framework supports multiple versions of R in the same framework, thus allowing parallel R versions to co-exist. By default R version @samp{x.y.z} will install into the @samp{Versions/x.y} subdirectory of the framework. The name of the subdirectory can be overridden by using @samp{FW_VERSION} configure setting, such as for example @samp{FW_VERSION=R-devel} which will install in @samp{Versions/R-devel}. The currently used framework is always the one pointed to by the @samp{Versions/Current}, see Apple's documentation on framework bundle anatomy for details (@uref{http://developer.apple.com/documentation/MacOSX/Conceptual/BPFrameworks/Concepts/FrameworkAnatomy.html}).

@node How to install R, How to build and install the R.app, How to configure and build R, Building R from sources
@section How to install R
Once the compilation succeeds type:
@example
sudo make install
@end example
to install R in @emph{/Library/Frameworks} (unless changed at configure time). You must have admin privileges and your password will be required.

You can decide to change the installation destination by using the @emph{prefix} option:
final destination.
@example
sudo make prefix=/my/new/R/location install
@end example
As in the above, you don't need to specify the name @emph{R.framework} in the path. (See R documentation for details.)

