@section How to build and install the R.app
The sources for the @Rapp{} GUI are currently not included in the global R source distribution. They are available in the form of a Xcode project on the R for Mac OS X @CRAN{} pages (released versions) as well as the SVN repository. In order to check out the latest development version, use
@example
svn co https://svn.r-project.org/R-packages/trunk/Mac-GUI
@end example
Before compiling @Rapp{} make sure @R{} is installed in @emph{/Library/Frameworks/R.framework} and working.

Using Xcode load the @emph{R.xcodeproj} project, select @emph{R} target (which is the default), set @emph{Deployment} configuration build. The same effect can be achieved on the command line in the @file{Mac-GUI} directory by typing:
@example
xcodebuild -target R -configuration Deployment
@end example

The current development is done using Xcode 3.1 or higher. The default
deployment build is universal, therefore you will need universal R
framework and Mac OS X 10.4u SDK. Make sure @file{/Library} is available
inside the SDK, recent Xcode installations ensure this automatically.

Note that other targets, e.g. @code{Lion64} may be needed for recent
versions of Xcode.

@c For compatibility, the GUI offers an old-style project for Xcode 2.0
@c named @file{R.xcode} which will build PowerPC binary only. However, this
@c project file is no longer actively maintained. 

In addition to the default @code{Deployment} configuration there is also
@code{Deployment64} configuration that build 64-bit version of the GUI -
you must have 64-bit R framework and Mac OS X 10.5 or higher for this to
work. Other useful configurations include @code{Leopard},
@code{Leopard64}, @code{SnowLeopard}, @code{Lion}, @code{Lion64} and
@code{Debug}.

The build includes both @Rapp{} and this `R for Mac OS X FAQ'.

@Rapp{} does not need to be installed in any specific way. Building @Rapp{} results in the @Rapp{} bundle which appears as one R icon. This application bundle can be run anywhere and it is customary to place it in the @emph{Applications} folder.

@node How to build universal R,  , How to build and install the R.app, Building R from sources
@section How to build universal R
Starting with @R{} 2.3.0 it is possible to build @R{} that runs on
multiple architectures: such @R{} build is called @emph{universal}. The
current application is to build 32-bit and 64-bit Intel versions of @R{}.

In order to be able to build universal R, all necessary libraries must
be available as @samp{i386} and @samp{x86_64} binaries. For system
libraries this is the default for Mac OS X on Intel Macs.  Other
libraries such as @code{readline} must be compiled accordingly.

In addition, the compilers must support both architectures. You will
need Xcode Developer Tools version 2.4.0 or higher and a Fortran
compiler that can create universal binaries. Such compilers are
available from @uref{http://r.research.att.com/tools/}.

The next step is to build a binary for each architecture.

Configure, build and install the @samp{i386} binary (assuming
@samp{R-2.15.2.tar.gz} is in the current directory, replace
@samp{R-2.15.2} with any other version or name as appropriate):
@example
tar fxz R-2.15.2.tar.gz
mkdir R-i386
cd R-i386
../R-2.15.2/configure r_arch=i386 CC="gcc -arch i386" \
CXX="g++ -arch i386" F77="gfortran -arch i386" \
FC="gfortran -arch i386" OBJC="gcc -arch i386"
make
make install
cd ..
@end example

Depending on your permissions, you may need to run @samp{sudo make
install}. The next step is to build and install the @samp{x86_64} binary:

@example
mkdir R-x86_64
cd R-x86_64
../R-2.15.2/configure r_arch=x86_64 CC="gcc -arch x86_64" \
CXX="g++ -arch x86_64" F77="gfortran -arch x86_64" \
FC="gfortran -arch x86_64" OBJC="gcc -arch x86_64"
make
make install
cd ..
@end example

The installation scripts in @R{} are sophisticated enough to merge both
builds together and create a universal @R{} framework. One crucial
requirement for this to work is to use @samp{i386} and @samp{x86_64} as
the architecture names.  Other supported architecture names are
@code{ppc} and @code{ppc64} (where supported by the OS). One @R{}
installation can contain all four architectures.

@c Since Mac OS X 10.4.8 @samp{vecLib} is now multi-threaded, so there is no need for threaded ATLAS anymore and the corresponding static library is no longer included in the toolbox.

Finally, the standard @R{} shell script uses by default the last installed architecture. This is probably not what you want, because the native architecture is known at run time. Therefore the line
@example
: $@{R_ARCH=/i386@}
@end example
can be replaced by
@example
: $@{R_ARCH=/`arch`@}.
@end example
to default to the current native architecture. It addition, it may be a
good idea to make sure that the @samp{PATH} environment variable
contains the path to your universal compiler, otherwise there may be
problems with compilation of universal packages. Those are also
modifications that you will find in the @CRAN{} release as compared to
vanilla R (plus the default of package type being binary instead of
source).

To run a specific architecture use the @samp{--arch} flag when starting
@R{}, e.g.@:, @samp{R --arch x86_64} for 64-bit R on Intel platform.
Note that the `native architecture' is @code{i386} on all Intel-based
Macs, whereas you probably do want @code{x86_64}.

@CRAN{} installations of @R{} (but not @Rapp{}) on Mac OS X 10.6 (Snow
Leopard) and 10.7 (Lion) default to 64-bit if the host CPU supports it
(and all Macs since mid 2008 do).  This will apply to 10.8 (Mountain
Lion) in future, but did not for @R{} 2.15.2.

@node Command line version of R, R.app, Building R from sources, Top
@chapter Command line version of R

The command line version of @R{} is almost identical to @R{} as used on
other unix-like operating systems. Therefore general documentation for
@R{} applies to this version as well.  On each release ready-to-use
binaries are distributed through @CRAN{}.  These binaries come with a
common installer used by @Rapp{} so please read the related notes
(@pxref{How to get R.app}).

On recent versions of OS X (Snow Leopard and later) the installer links
three executables in @file{/usr/bin}, @code{R32}, @code{R64} and
@code{R}.  The first is 32-bit, the second is 64-bit and @code{R} is
64-bit on Snow Leopard and Lion and later but 32-bit on Leopard (and
currently on Mountain Lion).  It also links @code{Rscript} (of the same
default architecture as @code{R}).

One thing that is different from @R{} on any other unix-like is the way
output is displayed on a terminal.  Except for `dumb' terminals,
messages to @file{stderr} are diverted to @file{stdout} and displayed in
bold using ANSI terminal escapes.

@c links to /usr/bin/R these days.
@c To use @R{} you probably need to add a symbolic link on your system as
@c the @R{} binary is located inside the framework.  Suppose you have the
@c @emph{/usr/local/bin} directory on your system (if you do not have one,
@c you can use @emph{/usr/bin} instead) you should just type in your
@c Terminal (a root password is required)
@c @example
@c sudo ln -s /Library/Frameworks/R.framework/Resources/R /usr/local/bin/R
@c @end example
@c Assuming that you have @emph{/usr/local/bin} in your @emph{PATH}
@c environment variable, you will be able to launch R from any location on
@c your system just by typing @emph{R}. In this way, when you install a new
@c version of the @emph{R.framework} this link will point to the latest R
@c binary.

