@chapter Tcl/Tk issues

Each binary distribution of @R{} available through @CRAN{} is built to
use the X11 implementation of Tcl/Tk.  Of course a X windows server has
to be started first: this should happen automatically on OS X, but can
take quite a while to do so.

@c If you are not using the @Rapp{} you need to also
@c define the environment variable DISPLAY before attempting to use X11 from inside @R{} (Mac OS X 10.4 and earlier only!). You can do this as follows
@c @example
@c Sys.setenv(DISPLAY=":0")
@c @end example

If you don't like the X11 style of widgets you would probably want to
build R using the Aqua version of Tcl/Tk (@pxref{Aqua Tcl/Tk headers and
libraries (optional)}).

Mac OS X 10.5 and later come with a ``feature'' that changes the way
X11 server is setup. As a consequence the @env{DISPLAY} environment
variable should not be touched or it will impede that mechanism. The
good part is that it should start X11 automatically.

@node Internationalization of the R.app, Additional resources, Tcl/Tk issues, Top
@chapter Internationalization of the R.app
@R{} and the @Rapp{} GUI introduced support for internationalization in R 2.1.0. Among other things this means that both messages and GUI elements can be translated into various languages. @Rapp{} automatically detects user's settings in the @emph{International} section of the System Preferences and uses that information to offer translated messages and GUI if available. Please note that both @emph{Language} and @emph{Formats} information is used so they should be set up consistently.

If you use a non-standard setup (e.g.@: different language than
formats), you can override the auto-detection performed by setting
@samp{force.LANG} defaults setting, such as for example
@example
defaults write org.R-project.R force.LANG en_US.UTF-8
@end example
when run in @emph{Terminal} it will enforce US-english setting regardless of the system setting. If you don't know what @emph{Terminal} is you can use this @R{} command instead:
@example
system("defaults write org.R-project.R force.LANG en_US.UTF-8")
@end example
but do not forget to quit @R{} and start @Rapp{} again afterwards. Please note that you must always use @samp{.UTF-8} version of the locale, otherwise @Rapp{} will not work properly.

Another change from previous versions (R 2.0 and @Rapp{} 1.01) is the support for UTF-8 character encoding. By default @Rapp{} uses UTF-8 for newly created documents and for the console. When opening new documents @Rapp{} assumes UTF-8 and only if the document violates UTF-8 rules, it will try to fallback to legacy encoding, usually Mac Roman.

If you are interested in translating @Rapp{} GUI into other languages, please read the developer documentation @uref{http://developer.r-project.org/Translations.html} for details.

